  "signature": "ed25519:bb9b8e5bafe77581addb6b5a69576211efb55506b2917457aa8aa42fede2fca0566e31bd2f592e04ac8795a8ac56490f061b07afc2e167e606717e2cd57f8905",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/sqa-level2",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R1 is a commercially validated solver with documented V&V suite. DePuy Synthes FEA team operates under ISO 13485 quality management system with documented change control and version management. FDA CDRH internal FEA group follows NIST-traceable software qualification procedures. All three ensemble members have current software qualification records on file. Achieved Gradation 3: formal QMS-controlled SQA with documented test suite and release notes reviewed against COU requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/code-verification-level2",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical benchmark suite includes patch tests, beam-bending analytical comparisons, and contact verification problems documented in the Ansys Verification Manual. The pedicle screw FEA employs linear hexahedral and tetrahedral elements whose convergence behavior has been verified against Timoshenko beam theory for the titanium rod component. Code verification at Gradation 2 confirmed: element formulations verified against published analytical solutions for geometrically similar structural problems."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/discretization-level3",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study performed on the non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry using three systematically refined meshes (coarse: ~85k elements, medium: ~210k elements, fine: ~520k elements). Richardson extrapolation applied to stiffness and yield force QoIs. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for the medium mesh relative to fine mesh is 1.8% for stiffness and 2.3% for yield force, both below the 5% acceptance threshold. The medium mesh was selected for production runs, achieving Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error is scoped out of this assessment because the ASTM F1717 compression-bending simulation is a quasi-static, geometrically linear analysis with small displacements in the elastic regime up to yield. No iterative nonlinear solver convergence issues have been identified across any of the three ensemble runs; residual norms fall below 1e-8 at every load step. The dominant source of numerical error in this COU is discretization, which is fully assessed. Solver truncation and round-off errors are negligible relative to model-form and input uncertainties for this class of problem, as confirmed by double-precision arithmetic in all ensemble members."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/use-error-level2",
      "rationale": "Model setup and execution followed a documented simulation plan reviewed by two independent analysts (FDA CDRH and DePuy Synthes). Boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, and load application were independently verified by a third analyst prior to production runs. A pre-run checklist consistent with ASME V&V 40 Table 3 requirements was completed and archived. Gradation 2 achieved: independent review of simulation inputs and boundary conditions documented prior to result extraction."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-form-level3",
      "rationale": "The FEA model employs isotropic linear elastic material models for Ti-6Al-4V (screw and rod) and UHMWPE (vertebral body surrogate) consistent with published material characterization data. Contact between screw and rod is modeled as frictional (mu=0.3, penalty method) with surface-to-surface contact pairs. The ASTM F1717 test geometry (two vertebral body surrogates, anterior plate or rod-screw construct) is replicated with CAD-accurate geometry from manufacturer drawings. Model form assumptions are documented and compared against the experimental setup; all simplifications (e.g., rigid vertebral body blocks replaced by elastic surrogates) are justified. Gradation 3: model form assumptions documented, justified against experimental evidence, and sensitivity of QoIs to key assumptions quantified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-inputs-level3",
      "rationale": "Material properties (elastic modulus, yield strength, Poisson's ratio) for Ti-6Al-4V sourced from ASTM F136 material certificates for the specific production lot used in bench testing. UHMWPE block properties taken from ISO 5834-2 characterization data. Geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of test specimens (n=3 screw samples measured). Probabilistic sensitivity analysis (Monte Carlo, 10,000 samples) performed on material property inputs; coefficient of variation in stiffness QoI attributable to input uncertainty is 2.1%, within acceptable bounds. Gradation 3: inputs traceable to measurements with documented uncertainty characterization."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-samples-level3",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: n=6, Lab 2: n=5). All specimens sourced from a single production lot with documented dimensional inspection and material certification. Specimen preparation followed ASTM F1717-15 Section 7. Dimensional measurements (screw outer diameter, rod diameter, pedicle fixation length) recorded for each specimen and used to update FEA geometry. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for stiffness is 4.2%, confirming acceptable specimen consistency. Gradation 3: multiple specimens across multiple laboratories with dimensional characterization."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-conditions-level2",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single load configuration (ASTM F1717 static compression-bending at 10 mm/min crosshead displacement rate, room temperature, ambient humidity). Both laboratories used calibrated servo-hydraulic test frames with NIST-traceable load cell calibration certificates current within 12 months of testing. Test conditions documented in laboratory notebooks archived per ISO 13485 record-retention requirements. Achieved Gradation 2: test conditions documented with calibrated instrumentation. Note: only a single test condition (compression-bending) is evaluated; torsion and tension-bending are outside the COU scope for this submission."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/equiv-inputs-level3",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was prepared mapping each FEA input parameter to its experimental counterpart, including material properties, geometry, boundary conditions, and loading. For each parameter pair, the source of the experimental value, the method of transfer to the FEA, and any transformation assumptions are documented. Dimensional measurements from CMM were directly used to set FEA geometry; no surrogate or estimated values were employed for primary QoI-driving parameters. Gradation 3: formal equivalency documentation with traceability from experimental measurements to model inputs confirmed by independent reviewer."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/output-comparison-level3",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed using the ASME V&V 20 validation metric E/uval for all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm). Experimental uncertainty uexp estimated from inter-specimen variability (95% CI) and inter-laboratory variability. Numerical uncertainty unum estimated from GCI analysis. Combined validation uncertainty uval = sqrt(uexp^2 + unum^2). Results: stiffness E/uval = 0.87 (pass, <1.96); yield force E/uval = 1.21 (pass); force at 40 mm E/uval = 1.43 (pass). Percentage differences: stiffness 3.2%, yield force 5.8%, force at 40 mm 7.1%, all within the pre-specified <10% acceptance bound. Gradation 4: formal V&V 20 validation metric applied with full uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Relevance of the quantities of interest is scoped out as a separately assessed factor because the QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly specified in the ASTM F1717 standard and are the regulatory submission quantities required by FDA guidance for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions. Their clinical and regulatory relevance is established by the standard itself and the FDA's own use of these metrics in predicate comparisons. A separate QoI relevance justification document (ref: FDA-CDRH-OST-2023-QoI-F1717) is on file and incorporated by reference. Treating this as a standalone factor would duplicate content already addressed in the COU intendedUse and decision record rationale."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU is scoped out because the validation activities ARE the COU: COU1 is defined as the validation of the FEA model against ASTM F1717 bench testing for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw. There is no extrapolation from a surrogate validation domain to a separate use domain; the test conditions, geometry, loading, and QoIs in the validation experiments are identical to those in the COU. A separate factor assessment would be circular. This scoping decision is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 6.3.2 guidance that relevance factors may be scoped out when the validation domain and the COU domain are co-incident."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The FEA model ensemble for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending achieves the required credibility level for a Medium model risk / Medium decision consequence COU. All ten assessed factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels. Three factors (Numerical solver error, Relevance of QoIs, Relevance of validation activities to COU) are scoped out with documented rationale: solver error is negligible for this quasi-static linear problem; QoI relevance is established by ASTM F1717 and FDA guidance; and validation-to-COU relevance is trivially satisfied because the validation domain is co-incident with the COU. The quantitative validation metric E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs, and all percentage differences are within the pre-specified 10% acceptance bound. The multi-laboratory, multi-specimen experimental dataset (N=11) provides robust experimental uncertainty characterization. The full provenance chain from bench test data through FEA ensemble predictions to validation metric computation is documented and archived. The credibility assessment team unanimously accepts this model for the stated COU.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
